IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: *This stop was captured on in-car and body worn camera* CASE #: 23-MSP-009469 SUSPECT(S): Hines, Zhane Nicole Ernestine (B/F DOB: 02/07/1995) margin-left:8px">Bryant, Khaya Monet (B/F DOB: 10/03/1997) VICTIM: Society NARRATIVE: On March 15, 2023 at approximately 1843 hours, I was on duty and in uniform operating unmarked MSP vehicle P-11. I was on routine patrol in the area of Aviation Boulevard at Cromwell Park Drive, Anne Arundel County, Maryland, when I first observed the suspect vehicle. While in lane 2 and stationary at the traffic signal, I observed the suspect vehicle approaching my location in lane 1 without a front license plate attached. The vehicle pulled alongside the driver side of my vehicle and I observed the vehicle had a rear Maryland registration plate attached. After the light changed, I activated my emergency equipment to conduct a lawful traffic stop on the suspect vehicle. The vehicle stopped on the right shoulder of Aviation Boulevard prior to Allwood Drive, Anne Arundel County, Maryland. The vehicle was a white Hyundai Accent bearing Maryland registration 8FA1403. I made a driver side approach to the vehicle and made contact with the driver and front seat passenger. The driver of the vehicle stated that the vehicle was in an accident and was waiting for the bumper to be replaced before attaching the license plate. The driver was identified by her Maryland issued drivers license as Zhane Nicole Ernestine Hines (B/F DOB: 02/07/1995). The passenger of the vehicle was identified as the second registered owner of the vehicle, Khaya Monet Bryant (B/F DOB: 10/03/1997). As I was speaking with the occupants, I detected the odor of cannabis emitting from the passenger compartment of the vehicle. When I asked the occupants about the odor, Bryant stated that she was smoking before she was picked up by Hines and both denied any contraband being in the vehicle. A probable cause search of the vehicle was conducted. During the search, I located a small black satchel behind the driver seat on the rear passenger floorboard. Inside the bag, I located a clear plastic baggie containing a greenish brown vegetable matter suspected to be cannabis, an orange cylindrical pill bottle containing a greenish brown vegetable matter suspected cannabis, and a green cylindrical grinder containing a greenish brown vegetable matter suspected cannabis. Under the bag, I further located a black ashtray containing a white hand rolled cigarette of a greenish brown vegetable matter suspected cannabis. No other contraband was recovered as a result of the search. I identified the contraband as cannabis based on my training, knowledge, and experience as a Maryland State Trooper. I am a graduate of the Maryland State Police Training Academy where I received over 40 hours of training relating to the identification of controlled dangerous substances and drug paraphernalia. Over the course of my career, I have made numerous drug seizures to include, but not limited to, cannabis. DISPOSITION The suspected cannabis was secured in my vehicle to be transported to the Maryland State Police Glen Burnie Barrack and processed according to MSP policy. Bryant admitted to possession of the cannabis and was issued a civil citation for possession of a personal use amount of cannabis while Hines was issued a warning for the associated traffic offense. Both subjects were released from the scene after being charged accordingly. The suspected cannabis was transported to the Maryland State Police Glen Burnie Barrack and processed according to MSP policy. The suspected cannabis was logged on MSP PH #P-343272 and weighed before being secured in Barrack P temp storage. The suspected cannabis from the satchel was found to have a weight of 9.5 grams, and the suspected cannabis cigarette was found to have a weight of 3.4 grams. All weights were verified by Cpl. Wiest #4939. All events occurred in Anne Arundel County, Maryland.
